"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439477","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-01-11","<p>Across Government, the government communications profession saved £330 million for taxpayers last year compared to 2009 to 2010 - by making its campaigns more cost effective. This means that we reduced communications spending by a total of £1 billion during the last Parliament.</p><p>The Health and Safety Executive employs six full time press officers. No press officer is paid more than £50,000. The total cost of running the press office In 2014/15 was £858,000, including staff payroll costs of £291,000 and media monitoring, evaluation and other support services of £567,000.</p><p>The National Employment Savings Trust Corporation employs the equivalent of 3.3 full time staff to deliver press and public relations. One person is paid over £50,000 per annum. The total cost of running the press office in 2014/15 was £193,000, including staff payroll costs of £124,000 and non-staff costs of £69,000.</p><p>The Pensions Regulator employs two people in their press office, both of whom earn over £50,000 per annum. The total cost of running the press office in 2014/15 was £364,000, including staff payroll costs of £316,000 and media monitoring service costs of £48,000.</p><p>The Pension Protection Fund employs two members of staff whose duties are primarily related to press and public relations. One of these members of staff earns more than £50,000 per annum. The total cost of running the press office in 2014/15 was £169,000, including staff payroll costs of £132,000 and supplier costs of £37,000.</p><p>The Pensions Advisory Service, Pensions Ombudsman and Pensions Protection Fund Ombudsman do not have a press office, or employ any press or public relations staff. Since August 2015, the Pensions Ombudsman has engaged a part time Communications Manager at a salary less than £50,000 per annum.</p><p>The Disabled People’s Employment Corporation (GB) Ltd is a non-trading company, managing legacy issues following the sale of Remploy Ltd into the private sector in April 2015. DPEC is winding up its affairs and now employs no staff. In 2014/15, the company employed four staff in its Marketing Communications department, all earning over £50,000 per annum. The total cost of running the press office in 2014/15 was £418,000.</p><br />","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-01-11T14:42:31.413Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439477/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439477/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439477/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-12-17","Department for Work and Pensions: Information Officers","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many press and public relations are employed by (a) the Disabled People's Employment Corporation, (b) Health and Safety Executive, (c) National Employment Savings Trust Corporation, (d) Pensions Advisory Service, (e) Pensions Regulator, (f) Pension Protection Fund Ombudsman, (g) Pensions Ombudsman, (h) Pension Protection Fund; how many of those employees were paid more than (i) £50,000 and (ii) £100,000; and what the total cost of running press office in each of those organisations was in the most recent period for which figures are available.","false","Biography information for Diana Johnson","Kingston upon Hull North","Diana Johnson","20608"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439478","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-01-05","<p>The Strategic Business Case was submitted and signed off by HMT in 2014. As HMT colleagues stated at the PAC on 7 December (link below) the Outline Business Case was approved in December 2015 and the Full Business Case will be submitted in 2017.</p><br /><p><a href="http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201314/cmselect/cmworpen/1082/1082.pdf" target="_blank">http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201314/cmselect/cmworpen/1082/1082.pdf</a></p>","Witham","Priti Patel","20624","2016-01-05T13:34:39.137Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439478/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439478/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439478/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-12-17","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, when he expects to submit the full business case for universal credit to HM Treasury; and when he expects final approval of that case to be granted.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","20625"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439479","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-01-05","<p>The Department continually monitors published reports in the public domain. This includes those which relate to policies in the Welfare Reform and Work Bill, which is currently being discussed in Committee in the House of Lords.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-01-05T12:05:58.593Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439479/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439479/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439479/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-12-17","Welfare Reform and Work Bill","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, pursuant to the Answer of 17 December 2015 to Question 20080, by what date his Department will review all reports which relate to the Welfare Reform and Work Bill; and whether his Department will publish a response to or make a statement on those reports after completing that review.","false","Biography information for Mr Roger Godsiff","Birmingham, Hall Green","Mr Roger Godsiff","20662"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439480","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-01-05","<p>The main and most robust finding in the report is that UC has a substantial impact on the chances of people moving into work after they make a new claim. UC claimants were 8 percentage points more likely to get a job within 270 days of claiming than equivalent new claims to JSA made at the same time in similar areas by similar individuals.</p><br /><p>The report and the peer review also set out findings on earnings. These are consistent with the extra people in work and suggest that the policy is working by making it more worthwhile and easier for claimants to do small amounts of work. That is, UC ensures that all work pays.</p><br /><p>Most of the findings on earnings are statistically significant. As the report explains, we will be able to improve these estimates over time as we get more data.</p><br />","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-01-05T13:58:16.167Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439480/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439480/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439480/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-12-17","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, with reference to the report entitled, Estimating the Early Labour Market Impacts of Universal Credit, published by his Department in December 2015, what assessment he has made of the implications for his policies of (a) the finding reported on page 27, that the additional work undertaken by participants in the study who were claiming universal credit is likely to consist of relatively few hours at relatively low wages and (b) the findings of the independent peer review, published in Annex B of the report, that the differences between the earnings of people in receipt of universal credit and people in the control group were not satisfactory significant.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","20632"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439481","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-01-05","<p>Following a successful Proof of Concept stage, national roll-out of the Universal Credit In-Work Progression Randomised Control Trial commenced from 7 December 2015. Recruitment into the trial will continue until the target sample of 15,000 in-work participants is achieved. We currently expect to reach this number by Autumn 2016, after which time the trial will continue to run for a period of 12 months. An evaluation report will follow in 2018.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-01-05T14:25:28.48Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439481/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439481/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439481/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-12-17","Social Security Benefits: Disqualification","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, with reference to page 7 of the Government's response to the Fifth Report from the Work and Pensions Committee, on Benefit Sanctions: Beyond the Oakley Review, HC 557, when the Government plans to publish the results of its evaluation of the pilot programme of in-work sanctions.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","20633"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439482","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-01-05","<p>An estimate of the overall impact on self-employment is not available. The Minimum Income Floor is intended to encourage those reporting very low self-employed income to increase their earnings either through increasing their earnings from self-employment, or through other employment.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-01-05T13:41:09.507Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439482/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439482/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439482/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-12-17","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what assessment he has made of the effect of uprating the Minimum Income Floor for the self-employed on universal credit inline with the National Minimum Wage on the number of people moving into self-employment.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","20657"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439483","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-01-05","<p>A person who meets the eligibility requirements for claiming Universal Credit (UC) anywhere in Great Britain where UC is available can claim contributory-only Jobseeker’s Allowance, either alongside a UC claim or on its own. If a person meets the conditions for claiming UC they cannot claim income-based Jobseeker’s Allowance.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-01-05T13:55:56.237Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439483/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439483/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439483/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-12-17","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, under what circumstances a person within one of the universal credit north west pathfinder jobcentres, who meets the eligibility criteria for universal credit under the pathfinder programme, may start a claim for jobseeker's allowance instead of universal credit.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","20615"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439484","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-01-05","I have done so, on the 17 December 2015.","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2016-01-05T11:45:49.363Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439484/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439484/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439484/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-12-17","Department for Work and Pensions: Written Questions","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, when he plans to answer Question 19086, tabled on 8 December 2015.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","20642"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439485","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-01-05","<p>There are no plans to amend the work allowances and taper rates beyond those set out by the Government at the 2015 Autumn Statement.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-01-05T14:06:24.497Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439485/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439485/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439485/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-12-17","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, whether he plans to reform the (a) work allowances and (b) taper rate within universal credit during the current Parliament.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","20620"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439486","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-01-05","<p>By 2020 Universal Credit (UC) will extend support to over a million more claimants than under Jobseeker’s Allowance. The majority of people in this group are not in work and currently have no employment support available. A small proportion of the group may be earning very small amounts - less than the Administrative Earnings Threshold - and will benefit from the out of work support.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-01-05T14:16:26.437Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439486/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439486/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439486/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-12-17","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, with reference to paragraph 2.50 of the Spending Review and Autumn Statement 2015, to which claimants the announcement of an extension of job search conditionality relates.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","20621"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439487","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-01-05","<p>The assessment of the Universal Support trials is currently underway. The final evaluation will be published in late Spring 2016 and this will include the numbers of those who participated in the trials and the evaluation.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel","20623","2016-01-05T14:01:43.63Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439487/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439487/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439487/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-12-17","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people in each of the 11 pilot areas of universal support delivered locally (a) participated in that programme and (b) consented to have their information used for the purposes of evaluating that programme between September 2014 and September 2015.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","20622"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439488","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-01-05","<p>The assessment of the Universal Support trials is currently underway. The final evaluation will be published in late Spring 2016 and this will include the numbers of those who participated in the trials and the evaluation.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel","20622","2016-01-05T14:01:43.693Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439488/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439488/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439488/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-12-17","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what plans he has to evaluate the Universal Support Delivered Locally programme on completion of the pilot study.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","20623"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439489","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-01-05","<p>The Strategic Business Case was submitted and signed off by HMT in 2014. As HMT colleagues stated at the PAC on 7 December (link below) the Outline Business Case was approved in December 2015 and the Full Business Case will be submitted in 2017.</p><br /><p><a href="http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201314/cmselect/cmworpen/1082/1082.pdf" target="_blank">http://www.publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201314/cmselect/cmworpen/1082/1082.pdf</a></p>","Witham","Priti Patel","20625","2016-01-05T13:34:39.09Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439489/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439489/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439489/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-12-17","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, when he (a) submitted and (b) received a response to (i) the strategic outline business case and (ii) the outline business case for universal credit from HM Treasury.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","20624"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439490","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-01-05","<p>The information requested is not available.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-01-05T13:51:45.307Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439490/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439490/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439490/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-12-17","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many people within each of the four Universal Credit North West Pathfinder jobcentres who meet the eligibility criteria for claiming universal credit under the Pathfinder programme have started a claim for jobseeker's allowance since the launch of universal credit in each of those jobcentres.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","20647"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439491","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-01-05","<p>The digital service is currently in operation in areas of Sutton, Croydon and London Bridge. Between January and April 2016 Hounslow, Musselburgh, Purley, Thornton Heath and Great Yarmouth will begin delivering the full Universal Credit service.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-01-05T14:11:54.89Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439491/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439491/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439491/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-12-17","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, in which areas the digital service for universal credit is (a) in operation and (b) expected to be in operation by April 2016.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","20648"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439492","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-01-11","<p>We have no plans to publish further distributional analysis. Changes to work allowances are one part of a package of changes to the tax and welfare systems at the Summer Budget and Autumn Statement, which are intended to move Britain from a low wage, high welfare economy to a high wage, lower welfare economy.</p><br />","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-01-11T16:29:45.97Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439492/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439492/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439492/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-12-17","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, if he will undertake a distributional analysis of the effect of recent changes to the work allowances within universal credit.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","20649"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439493","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-01-11","<p>Universal Credit (UC)is fundamentally different from the current legacy benefit system and supports more people into work and encourages them to earn more. We expect up to 300,000 more people to be in work as a result of UC.</p><p>The Government has committed to transitional arrangements as we reform the benefits and Tax Credit system. Those transferred by DWP from tax credits to UC will receive Transitional Protection. In addition, estimates of entitlements under UC of the sort requested are not available as they will vary depending on assumptions on the level of earnings.</p><br />","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-01-11T16:35:34.2Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439493/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439493/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439493/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-12-17","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what estimate he has made of the forecast number of people who will (a) move into work, (b) move out of poverty, (c) have increased income and (d) have increased of income of more than £25 a week following transition to universal credit.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","20650"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439494","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-01-05","<p>Following discussions with the external evaluation team it was agreed that an extension would enable the gathering of more robust evidence.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-01-05T13:47:37.47Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439494/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439494/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439494/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-12-17","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, for what reasons the six pilot areas for Universal Support Delivered Locally were selected for an additional six months extension from September 2015.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","20651"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439495","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-01-05","<p>The research finding that Universal Credit claimants appeared to be more flexible regarding the type of work they would consider is broadly consistent with other findings from the same research report that indicate that UC claimants are more engaged with the labour market than their JSA counterparts. UC claimants are spending longer on job search per week, and Universal Credit appears to be driving more active labour market behaviour, resulting in better labour market outcomes.</p><br /><p>The key finding from another recently published report entitled, ‘Estimating the Early Labour Market Impacts of Universal Credit’, is that UC has a substantial impact on the chances of people moving into work after they make a new claim. UC claimants were 8 percentage points more likely to get a job within 270 days of claiming than equivalent new claims to JSA made at the same time in similar areas by similar individuals.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-01-05T13:43:42.247Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439495/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439495/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439495/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-12-17","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, with reference to his Department's report, Universal Credit Extended Gateway Evaluation, published on 6 December 2015, what assessment he has made of the reasons for the report's finding on page 39, that participants in the study who were claiming universal credit were more flexible regarding the type of work they would consider at the outset than people claiming jobseeker's allowance.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","20577"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439496","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-01-05","<p>The report shows that 85% of people claiming Universal Credit thought the Claimant Commitment took into account all or some of their personal circumstances. Of that, 37% thought that <strong><em>all</em></strong> of the requirements in their Claimant Commitment took into account their personal circumstances and an additional 48% felt that <strong><em>some</em></strong> of the requirements of their claimant commitment took their personal circumstances into account.</p><br /><p>Universal Credit is having a positive impact on claimants’ movements into work. Other recently published research, ‘Estimating the Early Labour Market Impacts of Universal Credit’, demonstrates that UC has a substantial impact on the chances of people moving into work after they make a new claim. UC claimants were 8 percentage points more likely to get a job within 270 days of claiming than equivalent new claims to JSA made at the same time in similar areas by similar individuals.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-01-05T14:12:23.27Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439496/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439496/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439496/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-12-17","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, with reference to his Department's report, Universal Credit Extended Gateway Evaluation, published on 6 December 2015, what assessment he has made of the implications for his policies of the report's finding on page 13, that 37 per cent of people claiming universal credit felt that their claimant commitment took account of their personal circumstances.","false","Biography information for Emily Thornberry","Islington South and Finsbury","Emily Thornberry","20578"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439497","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2016-01-05","<p>The information requested is not currently available.</p><br /><p>The range of statistics published for Universal Credit has increased as quality assurance has been carried out. This process will continue on a wider range of breakdowns and Departmental statisticians anticipate being able to start releasing these, in accordance with the relevant protocols in the Code of Practice for Official Statistics, during 2016.</p>","Witham","Priti Patel",,"2016-01-05T11:47:11.103Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439497/answer","Biography information for Priti Patel","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439497/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439497/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2015-12-17","Universal Credit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, how many claimants have been provided with advance payments of universal credit in each of the last 12 months.","false","Biography information for Stephen Timms","East Ham","Stephen Timms","20559"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439498","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-01-05","<p>Private rented sector legislation as in the Housing Act 1988, and the Protection from Eviction Act 1977 sets out the rights of landlords and tenants. It is applicable to all tenants and landlords, and there are no specific protections for (a) all housing benefits claimants or (b) vulnerable tenants, other than their statutory rights in UK legislation.</p>","Great Yarmouth","Brandon Lewis",,"2016-01-05T15:51:59.84Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439498/answer","Biography information for Brandon Lewis","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439498/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439498/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-12-17","Housing Benefit","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Communities and Local Government, whether (a) all and (b) vulnerable tenants who receive housing benefit are subject to additional protection from eviction by landlords.","false","Biography information for Imran Hussain","Bradford East","Imran Hussain","20543"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439499","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-12-30","We are aware of reports on alleged violations of international humanitarian law in Yemen by the Saudi Arabian-led Coalition and take these very seriously. We have regularly raised with Saudi Arabia the need to comply with international humanitarian law in Yemen, and continue to engage with them on this. We have offered advice and training to demonstrate best practice and to help ensure continued compliance with international humanitarian law. The UK is satisfied that we are not in breach of our international obligations. The UK operates one of the most rigorous and transparent export control regimes in the world. All exports of arms and controlled military goods are assessed on a case-by-case basis against the Consolidated EU and National Arms Export Licensing Criteria, taking account of all relevant information at the time of the application, to ensure compliance with our legal obligations. A licence will not be issued, for any country, if to do so would be inconsistent with any provision of the UK Licensing Criteria, including where we assess there is a clear risk that it might be used in the commission of a serious violation of international humanitarian law.",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2015-12-30T14:22:28.137Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439499/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439499/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439499/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-12-17","Yemen: Military Intervention","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the analysis commissioned by Amnesty and Saferworld which concludes that the transfer of weapons capable of being used in the conflict in Yemen to Saudi Arabia constitutes a breach by the UK of its obligations under domestic and international law.","false","Biography information for Lord Ahmed",,"Lord Ahmed","HL4684"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439500","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-12-30","<p>We are aware of reports on alleged violations of international humanitarian law in Yemen by the Saudi Arabian-led Coalition and take these very seriously. We have regularly raised with Saudi Arabia the need to comply with international humanitarian law in Yemen, and continue to engage with them on this. We have offered advice and training to demonstrate best practice and to help ensure continued compliance with international humanitarian law. The Ministry of Defence monitors alleged international humanitarian law violations, using available information, which in turn informs our overall assessment of international humanitarian law compliance in Yemen. We consider a range of evidence from government sources, foreign governments, the media and international non-governmental organisations.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2015-12-30T14:23:06.923Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439500/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439500/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439500/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-12-17","Yemen: Military Intervention","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the reliability of assurances from the government of Saudi Arabia that it is complying with international humanitarian law in the conflict in Yemen, in the light of Saudi Arabia's history regarding its obligations under international law.","false","Biography information for Lord Ahmed",,"Lord Ahmed","HL4685"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439501","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-12-30","The UK supports the Saudi Arabian-led Coalition military intervention, which came at the request of legitimate President Hadi. We have been clear with all parties that military action should be taken in accordance with international humanitarian law. We are aware of reports on alleged violations of international humanitarian law in Yemen by the Saudi Arabian-led Coalition and take these very seriously. We have regularly raised with Saudi Arabia the need to comply with international humanitarian law in Yemen, and continue to engage with them on this. We have offered advice and training to demonstrate best practice and to help ensure continued compliance with international humanitarian law. The Ministry of Defence monitors alleged international humanitarian law violations, using available information, which in turn informs our overall assessment of international humanitarian law compliance in Yemen. We consider a range of evidence from government sources, foreign governments, the media and international non-governmental organisations. The UK is satisfied that we are not in breach of our international obligations. The UK operates one of the most rigorous and transparent export control regimes in the world. All exports of arms and controlled military goods to Saudi Arabia are assessed on a case-by-case basis against the Consolidated EU and National Arms Export Licensing Criteria, taking account of all relevant information at the time of the application, to ensure compliance with our legal obligations. A licence will not be issued, for any country, if to do so would be inconsistent with any provision of the UK Licensing Criteria, including where we assess there is a clear risk that it might be used in the commission of a serious violation of international humanitarian law.",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2015-12-30T14:24:32.05Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439501/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439501/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439501/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-12-17","Yemen: Military Intervention","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of whether the assurances by the government of Saudi Arabia that it is complying with international humanitarian law in its military intervention in Yemen suffice for the UK to meet its obligations under Article 6(3) of the Arms Trade Treaty.","false","Biography information for Lord Ahmed",,"Lord Ahmed","HL4686"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439502","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-12-30","We continue to raise the importance of compliance with human rights law with all sides to the conflict. We are aware of reports on alleged violations of international humanitarian law in Yemen by the Saudi Arabian-led Coalition and take these very seriously. We have regularly raised with Saudi Arabia the need to comply with international humanitarian law in Yemen, and continue to engage with them on this. We have offered advice and training to demonstrate best practice and to help ensure continued compliance with international humanitarian law. The Ministry of Defence monitors alleged international humanitarian law violations, using available information, which in turn informs our overall assessment of international humanitarian law compliance in Yemen. We consider a range of evidence from government sources, foreign governments, the media and international non-governmental organisations.",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2015-12-30T14:25:47.147Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439502/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439502/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439502/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-12-17","Yemen: Military Intervention","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the evidence concerning attacks by the Saudi Arabia-led coalition in Yemen and the risk that a breach of international humanitarian or human rights law will be committed by that coalition.","false","Biography information for Lord Ahmed",,"Lord Ahmed","HL4687"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439503","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-12-30","We are aware of reports of alleged violations of international humanitarian law in Yemen by the Saudi Arabian-led Coalition and take these very seriously. We have regularly raised with Saudi Arabia the need to comply with international humanitarian law in Yemen, and continue to engage with them on this. We have offered advice and training to demonstrate best practice and to help ensure continued compliance with international humanitarian law. The UK is satisfied that we are not in breach of our international obligations. The UK operates one of the most rigorous and transparent export control regimes in the world. All exports of arms and controlled military goods are assessed on a case-by-case basis against the Consolidated EU and National Arms Export Licensing Criteria, taking account of all relevant factors at the time of the application, to ensure compliance with our legal obligations. A licence will not be issued, for any country, if to do so would be inconsistent with any provision of the UK Licensing Criteria, including where we assess there is a clear risk that it might be used in the commission of a serious violation of international humanitarian law. Our export licensing system allows us to respond quickly to changed circumstances, with options to suspend or revoke licences if necessary.",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2015-12-30T14:26:54.387Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439503/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439503/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439503/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-12-17","Yemen: Military Intervention","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the risk that UK weapons are being used to commit or facilitate a breach of international humanitarian law, in the light of reports of indiscriminate airstrikes in Yemen by the Saudi Arabia-led coalition, including the destruction of schools and hospitals.","false","Biography information for Lord Ahmed",,"Lord Ahmed","HL4688"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439504","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-12-30","<p>The Government believes that recognition of genocides should be a matter for international courts. It should be a legal, rather than political determination, decided by international judges after consideration of all the evidence available in the context of a credible international judicial process.</p><p>However, we are funding a project that is documenting sexual violence in Iraq, in a victim sensitive way. This database of cases will then be used to help survivors access justice and ensure that perpetrators are held to account. We also co-sponsored the UN Human Rights Council Resolution mandating the UN to investigate and report on Daesh abuses.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2015-12-30T14:35:29.283Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439504/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439504/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439504/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-12-17","Genocide","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Baroness Anelay of St Johns on 16 December (HL4327) that "we are not submitting any evidence of possible genocide against Yezidis and Christians to international courts, nor have we been asked to", what assistance they are providing to the Assyrian Christians and Yezidis to make the case that genocide has been committed, and what resources they are providing for the collection of evidence.","false","Biography information for Lord Alton of Liverpool",,"Lord Alton of Liverpool","HL4689"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439505","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-01-06","<p>The Government is committed to reducing welfare spending and is confident that registered providers will be able to adapt and manage these changes. The Welfare Reform and Work Bill provides for registered providers to apply for an exemption from the rent reductions if their financial viability is jeopardised. However, we do not expect providers to budget on the basis that an exemption will be automatically granted, as they should be making all possible efforts to manage the reductions.</p><p>The Government has made an assessment of the impact of the rent reduction measures (attached). This is at http://www.parliament.uk/documents/impact-assessments/IA15-006F.pdf.</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2016-01-06T14:59:34.127Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439505/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439505/answer","HL4690.pdf","HL4690.pdf","Impact Assessment","Impact Assessment","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439505/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-12-17","Social Rented Housing","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether they have conducted a full assessment of the impact of the proposed one per cent cut in rent for social housing tenants on the eight Community Land Trusts (CLTs) that are Registered Providers and whether they will take steps to ensure exemptions for CLTs.","false","Biography information for Baroness Bakewell of Hardington Mandeville",,"Baroness Bakewell of Hardington Mandeville","HL4690"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439506","Department for Communities and Local Government","false","2016-01-05","<p>The Government will honour all existing funding commitments to all schemes which have been allocated funding through the 2015-18 Affordable Homes Programme. This will include any schemes led by Community Land Trusts and community-led housing providers</p>",,"Baroness Williams of Trafford",,"2016-01-05T16:54:02.267Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439506/answer","Biography information for Baroness Williams of Trafford","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439506/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439506/answer",,,,,"7","Communities and Local Government","Communities and Local Government","2015-12-17","Affordable Housing: Finance","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether the Spending Review announcements on funding for affordable housing and the forecast £1 billion remaining in the 2015–18 Affordable Homes Programme will mean the continuation of availability of grant to complete pipeline projects by Community Land Trusts and community-led housing providers, including for rental homes.","false","Biography information for Baroness Bakewell of Hardington Mandeville",,"Baroness Bakewell of Hardington Mandeville","HL4691"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439507","Department for Transport","false","2015-12-21","<p>The Northern Powerhouse Rail network develops the HS3 concept to offer a vision for radically improved journey times and service frequencies between the major cities of the North, building on the substantial rail improvements to which the government is already committed.</p><br /><p>In November, the government and Transport for the North published the Northern Transport Strategy: Autumn Report, providing a progress update on the Northern Powerhouse Rail network.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2015-12-21T14:35:17.74Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439507/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439507/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439507/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-12-17","Railways: North of England","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the remarks by Viscount Younger of Leckie on 10 December (HL Deb, col GC213), whether HS3 has now been subsumed into the Northern Powerhouse rail network.","false","Biography information for Lord Berkeley",,"Lord Berkeley","HL4692"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439508","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-01-04","<p>While the relevant local authority would be best placed to provide details on any specific measures, over recent decades, air quality has improved significantly. Between 2005 and 2013 emissions of nitrogen oxides have fallen by 38% and particulate matter has reduced by more than 16%. The Government is investing heavily in transport measures to reduce air pollution and since 2011 has committed £2 billion to increase the uptake of ultra-low emission vehicles, support green transport initiatives and support Local Authorities to take action.</p><br /><p>On 17 December, we issued the UK plan for improving air quality. It sets out a comprehensive approach that will reduce health impacts and meet our environmental and legal obligations. It is available on the GOV.UK website.</p><br />",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2016-01-04T11:45:55.703Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439508/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439508/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439508/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-12-17","Heathrow Airport: Air Pollution","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what measures they have taken since 2010 to reduce air pollution caused by traffic journeys to Heathrow airport and in its immediate vicinity, and what was the outcome of those measures.","false","Biography information for Lord Brooke of Alverthorpe",,"Lord Brooke of Alverthorpe","HL4693"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439509","Department of Health","false","2016-01-04","<p>The Scientific Advisory Committee on Nutrition published its report <em>Carbohydrates and Health</em> in July 2015, which found that consuming too much sugar can lead to weight gain. It recommended that no more than 5% of energy in our diet should be from sugar. We are currently consuming over double the recommended limit for sugar; with children and teenagers consuming around three times the recommended level.</p><p><strong></strong></p><p>A copy of <em>Carbohydrates and Health</em> is attached and available at:</p><p><strong></strong></p><p><a href="http://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/445503/SACN_Carbohydrates_and_Health.pdf" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/445503/SACN_Carbohydrates_and_Health.pdf</a></p><p /> <p>Alongside this, we requested that Public Health England (PHE), as an Executive Agency of the Department, to prepare evidence for the Government on reducing sugar consumption. We are currently working very closely with PHE and its evidence is integral to the development of our forthcoming childhood obesity strategy.</p><p /> <p>A copy of PHE’s report <em>Sugar Reduction: The evidence for action</em> is attached and available at:</p><p /> <p><a href="http://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/470179/Sugar_reduction_The_evidence_for_action.pdf" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/470179/Sugar_reduction_The_evidence_for_action.pdf</a></p><p /> <p>An analysis of the economic burden of a range of risk factors for chronic disease estimated that overweight and obesity cost the National Health Service £5.1 billion per year.</p><p /> <p>A copy of the analysis <em>The economic burden of ill health due to diet, physical inactivity, smoking, alcohol and obesity in the UK: an update to 2006-07 NHS costs</em> is attached and available at:</p><p /> <p><a href="http://jpubhealth.oxfordjournals.org/content/early/2011/05/11/pubmed.fdr033.full.pdf+html" target="_blank">http://jpubhealth.oxfordjournals.org/content/early/2011/05/11/pubmed.fdr033.full.pdf+html</a></p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton","HL4705","2016-01-04T14:17:36.73Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439509/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439509/answer","Economic burden of ill health.pdf ; PHE Sugar reduction report 2015.pdf ; SACN Carbohydrates and Health 2015.pdf","Economic burden of ill health.pdf ; PHE Sugar reduction report 2015.pdf ; SACN Carbohydrates and Health 2015.pdf","Economic Burden of Ill Health ; PHE Sugar Reduction Report ; SACN Carbohydrates & Health","Economic Burden of Ill Health ; PHE Sugar Reduction Report ; SACN Carbohydrates & Health","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439509/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-12-17","Sugar","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of whether there is a growing health problem at all ages connected to excess consumption of sugar, and if they consider that there is such a problem, what new measures they will take to reverse the trend.","false","Biography information for Lord Brooke of Alverthorpe",,"Lord Brooke of Alverthorpe","HL4694"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439510","HM Treasury","false","2016-01-06","<p>In 2012-13 it is estimated that 26.8m individuals are liable to National Insurance Contributions from earned income or self-employed profits across the different classes of National Insurance.</p><br /><p>This is estimated using the latest available outturn from the Survey of Personal Income (SPI) for 2012-13. The SPI does not contain information on the nationality of individuals in the sample.</p><br /><p>Calculating the number of individuals in 2012-13 who were paying National Insurance Contributions who were citizens of the EU when they first registered for a National Insurance number is complex and cannot be done quickly.However, HM Revenue and Customs are planning to produce more data early in 2016 on this issue.</p>",,"Lord O'Neill of Gatley",,"2016-01-06T14:40:17.493Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439510/answer","Biography information for Lord O'Neill of Gatley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439510/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439510/answer",,,,,"14","Treasury","CaTreasury","2015-12-17","National Insurance Contributions","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how many persons were paying National Insurance contributions in the most recent period for which data are available, and how many of those were citizens of the EU10 countries at the time they first registered for a National Insurance number.","false","Biography information for Lord Green of Deddington",,"Lord Green of Deddington","HL4695"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439511","Home Office","false","2016-01-06","<p>Between 1999 and 2005, several measures harmonising common minimum standards for asylum were adopted. The six measures were the Dublin II Regulation, the EURODAC Regulation, the Temporary Protection Directive, the Reception Conditions Directive, the Qualification Directive and the Asylum Procedures Directive. The UK opted into all of these Directives.</p><p>The Reception Conditions Directive, the Qualifications Directive and the Asylum Procedures Directives were later revised but the UK did not opt into the revised versions and remains bound by the original Directives.</p><p>The Dublin II Regulation and EURODAC Regulation were also revised and the UK opted into the revised versions.</p><p>The Temporary Protection Directive has not been revised and the UK remains bound by the original Directive.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2016-01-06T15:46:48.62Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439511/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439511/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439511/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-12-17","Asylum: EU Law","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what are the EU directives on asylum into which they have opted, and what are those from which they have opted out.","false","Biography information for Lord Green of Deddington",,"Lord Green of Deddington","HL4696"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439512","Department for Business, Innovation and Skills","false","2016-01-13","<p>The review of the UK unsafe product recall system chaired by Lynn Faulds Wood will be published soon.</p><br />",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2016-01-13T12:49:23.353Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439512/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439512/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439512/answer",,,,,"26","Business, Innovation and Skills","Business, Innovation and Skills","2015-12-17","Recall of Unsafe Products Review","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government when they anticipate the review of unsafe product recall, chaired by Lynn Faulds-Wood, will be published.","false","Biography information for Baroness Hayter of Kentish Town",,"Baroness Hayter of Kentish Town","HL4697"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439513","Department of Health","false","2016-01-05","<p>The Chief Medical Officer, with advice from a group of independent experts, has reviewed current drinking guidelines. The proposals will be published shortly.</p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton",,"2016-01-05T11:38:08.557Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439513/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439513/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439513/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-12-17","Alcoholic Drinks: Consumption","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Lord Prior of Brampton on 17 September (HL2043), when they expect to publish updated guidelines relating to lower-risk drinking.","false","Biography information for Baroness Hayter of Kentish Town",,"Baroness Hayter of Kentish Town","HL4698"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439514","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-12-23","<p>In our regular dialogue with the Ugandan government we stress the importance of protecting public order in a way that also protects the rights to freedom of expression and assembly. We are reinforcing that point with the Government of Uganda, bilaterally and with EU partners, in the run up to the February 2016 elections. The use of live ammunition by the Ugandan police to disperse crowds raises serious concerns about public safety.</p><p>Peaceful exercise of freedoms of speech and assembly is fundamental to any democratic society and is provided for and protected under Uganda’s constitution. During his visit to Uganda on 15 December, the Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, my hon. Friend the Member for Rochford and Southend East (James Duddridge), underlined that it is vital for Uganda’s future that the elections in 2016 are credible, inclusive and transparent, and that they are underpinned by a respect for human rights. An EU election observation mission will be deployed to Uganda later this month.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2015-12-23T15:04:21.56Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439514/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439514/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439514/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-12-17","Uganda: Elections","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of evidence that Ugandan police, in the run-up to the election in February 2016, have used live ammunition to disperse opposition gatherings, and have committed other serious human rights violations.","false","Biography information for Baroness Kinnock of Holyhead",,"Baroness Kinnock of Holyhead","HL4699"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439515","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-12-23","<p>The British Government remains supportive of the elections planned for 27 December in the Central African Republic (CAR). This date has been agreed by the transitional government and the international community. Elections in CAR have already been delayed this year. Further delays would allow armed groups and spoilers to enhance their position and strengthen their rhetoric. There must be an end to the transition phase in order to secure a stable peace, and allow reconciliation to begin. By 16 November, when voter registration closed, approximately 95 per cent of the estimated electorate were registered, which is a significant success for the CAR transitional authorities. Out-of-country voter registration of Central African refugees and diaspora progressed more slowly, with approximately one third of the estimated refugee electorate registered. In the referendum on 13 December, judged a success by a UN Security Council assessment, many of CAR’s population turned out determined to vote. Through the international community, we will work to ensure that an elected president appoints an inclusive government representative of CAR’s population. Due to the commitment of the international community to the election date, agreement was found for some 300 extra UN troops to be provided to ensure security during the election period.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2015-12-23T15:04:36.373Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439515/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439515/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439515/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-12-17","Central African Republic: Elections","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the case for pressing the government of the Central African Republic to delay the planned election until there is confidence that that election can be held safely and that all eligible voters will be on the electoral roll.","false","Biography information for Baroness Kinnock of Holyhead",,"Baroness Kinnock of Holyhead","HL4700"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439516","Home Office","false","2016-01-07","<p>The Investigatory Powers Tribunal (IPT) and any decision it makes are entirely independent of Government. The Home Office was not a named respondent in the case and we have made no assessment of the Tribunal’s decision.</p>",,"Lord Bates",,"2016-01-07T17:02:33.557Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439516/answer","Biography information for Lord Bates","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439516/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439516/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2015-12-17","Electronic Surveillance: USA","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the decision of the Investigatory Powers Tribunal in the case of children A and B in relation to Prism, heard on 10 December.","false","Biography information for Lord Laird",,"Lord Laird","HL4701"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439517","Northern Ireland Office","false","2015-12-23","<p>The Parades Commission for Northern Ireland is a specified public body under Part VII of the Freedom of Information Act 2000 and subject to the provisions of the Act.</p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2015-12-23T10:07:59.31Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439517/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439517/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439517/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2015-12-17","Parades Commission: Freedom of Information","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government whether the Northern Ireland Parades Commission can have its files and information accessed under the Freedom of Information Act 2000.","false","Biography information for Lord Laird",,"Lord Laird","HL4702"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439518","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-01-13","<p>As set out in the Public Records Act 1958 (as amended), public records selected for permanent preservation are transferred toThe National Archives or an approved place of deposit no later than 20 years after creation, unless an department is authorised to keep them for longer. Such decisions are undertakenwithadvice from the Advisory Council on National Records and Archives.</p><p>The Access to Public Records Manual published by the National Archives sets out the seven broad grounds for retention, which is attached.</p><br /><p>Retention instruments can cover multiple applicationsby departments to retain records and the number of applications covered by Lord Chancellor's Instruments 111-119 ranges from 37 to 253, which were submitted by between 8 and 15 departments.</p><br /><p>The grounds provided by departments that were given permission to retain records under Instruments 111, 113, 114 and 119 are 1,2,4 and 6. Records under Instruments 112, 115, 117 and 118 were retained on grounds 1, 4 and 6 and records under Instrument 116 were retained on grounds 4 and 6. Each of the Instruments therefore covers documents retained on grounds of national security, as well as other administrative reasons.</p><br /><p>There is a strong public interest in not releasing information which could undermine the safeguarding of national security.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2016-01-13T16:27:39.12Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439518/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439518/answer","access-to-public-records.pdf","access-to-public-records.pdf","National Archives Access to Public Records 2015","National Archives Access to Public Records 2015","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439518/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-12-17","Public Records","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Baroness Neville-Rolfe on 15 December (HL3615), in respect of each retention instrument, what were the reasons for deciding not to transfer records to the National Archives, and what was the subject matter of each instrument.","false","Biography information for Lord Lester of Herne Hill",,"Lord Lester of Herne Hill","HL4703"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439519","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-01-13","<p>As set out in the Public Records Act 1958 (as amended), public records selected for permanent preservation are transferred toThe National Archives or an approved place of deposit no later than 20 years after creation, unless an department is authorised to keep them for longer. Such decisions are undertakenwithadvice from the Advisory Council on National Records and Archives.</p><p>The Access to Public Records Manual published by the National Archives sets out the seven broad grounds for retention, which is attached.</p><p>Retention instruments can cover multiple applicationsby departments to retain records and the number of applications covered by Lord Chancellor's Instruments 111-119 ranges from 37 to 253, which were submitted by between 8 and 15 departments.</p><br /><p>The grounds provided by departments that were given permission to retain records under Instruments 111, 113, 114 and 119 are 1,2,4 and 6. Records under Instruments 112, 115, 117 and 118 were retained on grounds 1, 4 and 6 and records under Instrument 116 were retained on grounds 4 and 6. Each of the Instruments therefore covers documents retained on grounds of national security, as well as other administrative reasons.</p><br /><p>There is a strong public interest in not releasing information which could undermine the safeguarding of national security.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2016-01-13T17:09:13.627Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439519/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439519/answer","access-to-public-records.pdf","access-to-public-records.pdf","National Archives Access to Public Records 2015","National Archives Access to Public Records 2015","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439519/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-12-17","Public Records","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, further to the Written Answer by Baroness Neville-Rolfe on 15 December (HL3615), whether they will place retention instruments 111 to 119 in the Library of the House.","false","Biography information for Lord Lester of Herne Hill",,"Lord Lester of Herne Hill","HL4704"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439520","Department of Health","false","2016-01-04","<p>The Scientific Advisory Committee on Nutrition published its report <em>Carbohydrates and Health</em> in July 2015, which found that consuming too much sugar can lead to weight gain. It recommended that no more than 5% of energy in our diet should be from sugar. We are currently consuming over double the recommended limit for sugar; with children and teenagers consuming around three times the recommended level.</p><p><strong></strong></p><p>A copy of <em>Carbohydrates and Health</em> is attached and available at:</p><p><strong></strong></p><p><a href="http://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/445503/SACN_Carbohydrates_and_Health.pdf" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/445503/SACN_Carbohydrates_and_Health.pdf</a></p><p /> <p>Alongside this, we requested that Public Health England (PHE), as an Executive Agency of the Department, to prepare evidence for the Government on reducing sugar consumption. We are currently working very closely with PHE and its evidence is integral to the development of our forthcoming childhood obesity strategy.</p><p /> <p>A copy of PHE’s report <em>Sugar Reduction: The evidence for action</em> is attached and available at:</p><p /> <p><a href="http://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/470179/Sugar_reduction_The_evidence_for_action.pdf" target="_blank">www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/470179/Sugar_reduction_The_evidence_for_action.pdf</a></p><p /> <p>An analysis of the economic burden of a range of risk factors for chronic disease estimated that overweight and obesity cost the National Health Service £5.1 billion per year.</p><p /> <p>A copy of the analysis <em>The economic burden of ill health due to diet, physical inactivity, smoking, alcohol and obesity in the UK: an update to 2006-07 NHS costs</em> is attached and available at:</p><p /> <p><a href="http://jpubhealth.oxfordjournals.org/content/early/2011/05/11/pubmed.fdr033.full.pdf+html" target="_blank">http://jpubhealth.oxfordjournals.org/content/early/2011/05/11/pubmed.fdr033.full.pdf+html</a></p>",,"Lord Prior of Brampton","HL4694","2016-01-04T14:17:36.887Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439520/answer","Biography information for Lord Prior of Brampton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439520/answer","Economic burden of ill health.pdf ; PHE Sugar reduction report 2015.pdf ; SACN Carbohydrates and Health 2015.pdf","Economic burden of ill health.pdf ; PHE Sugar reduction report 2015.pdf ; SACN Carbohydrates and Health 2015.pdf","Economic Burden of Ill Health ; PHE Sugar Reduction Report ; SACN Carbohydrates & Health","Economic Burden of Ill Health ; PHE Sugar Reduction Report ; SACN Carbohydrates & Health","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439520/answer",,,,,"17","Health","Health","2015-12-17","Obesity","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government how much obesity-related conditions and illnesses cost the NHS annually; and what action they are taking in line with the recommendations of Public Health England to tackle obesity and the excessive consumption of sugar.","false","Biography information for The Marquess of Lothian",,"The Marquess of Lothian","HL4705"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439521","Department for Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","false","2016-01-04","<p>Defra publishes an annual indicator on butterfly abundance, using data collected by volunteers. Large fluctuations are typical of butterfly populations but in England the indicator shows that butterfly numbers have generally fallen since 1990, although with numbers of some common species stabilising over the last five years.</p><p>In England, we will take forward our manifesto commitment to produce a 25 year strategy for the environment, which will include biodiversity<em>. </em>Our approach will be designed to meet the habitat needs of many species including butterflies. In England’s National Pollinator Strategy we are aiming to expand flower rich habitats across different types of land to benefit pollinators including butterflies.</p><p>The England network of protected areas provides benefits for many species even when those areas are not specifically designated for the conservation of those particular species. This network includes local and national sites protected under domestic legislation and international sites protected under European and International law. Some of these sites are specifically designated for species of particular importance, including the marsh fritillary butterfly, which is a notified feature of a number of Special Areas of Conservation, designated under the Habitats Directive.</p><p>Agri-environment schemes play a major role in the conservation of butterflies in England. For instance, across grassland habitats in Dorset, between 1990 and 2010 the marsh fritillary increased in abundance by around 278% on land managed under these schemes.</p><p>In the summer of 2014 the critically endangered high brown fritillary experienced its best season since 2004 with numbers increasing by more than 180% as compared to 2013 across Dartmoor, Exmoor, and Morecambe Bay in Lancashire and sites in the Lake District.</p><p>The Wild Pollinator and Farm Wildlife Package in the new Countryside Stewardship scheme contain options to improve habitats and provide nectar sources for butterflies. It will play a key role in supporting the National Pollinator Strategy.</p>",,"Lord Gardiner of Kimble",,"2016-01-04T12:21:59.49Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439521/answer","Biography information for Lord Gardiner of Kimble","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439521/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439521/answer",,,,,"13","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","Environment, Food and Rural Affairs","2015-12-17","Butterflies","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the reported decline in the population of resident and regular migrant butterflies in the UK, and whether they are taking any action to prevent further decline.","false","Biography information for The Marquess of Lothian",,"The Marquess of Lothian","HL4706"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439522","Cabinet Office","false","2016-01-08","<p>The Independent Commission on Freedom of Information will report as soon as possible after the oral evidence sessions it has announced for 20 and 25 January.</p>",,"Lord Bridges of Headley",,"2016-01-08T14:04:37.56Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439522/answer","Biography information for Lord Bridges of Headley","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439522/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439522/answer",,,,,"53","Cabinet Office","Cabinet Office","2015-12-17","Commission on Freedom of Information","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government when they expect the Independent Commission on Freedom of Information to publish its report.","false","Biography information for The Marquess of Lothian",,"The Marquess of Lothian","HL4707"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439523","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2016-01-05","<p>Efficiency savings of £53 million by 2019-20 will be delivered, in part, through reducing the running costs of our global network and the use of improved technology. There will also be reductions to the non-Official Development Assistance funding for the British Council, although overall funding for the British Council will be protected in real terms.</p>",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2016-01-05T15:04:48.16Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439523/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439523/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439523/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-12-17","Foreign and Commonwealth Office: Cost Effectiveness","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government, in the light of the Spending Review 2015, where they expect the majority of the FCO efficiency savings of £53 million by 2019–20 will be made.","false","Biography information for The Marquess of Lothian",,"The Marquess of Lothian","HL4708"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439524","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2015-12-30","The Foreign and Commonwealth Office is committed to the promotion and protection of human rights globally and views the upholding of universal rights as intrinsic to all our bilateral work overseas and our support for the rules based international order. The UK’s decision to stand for re-election to the UN’s Human Rights Council in 2017 reflects the importance we attach to this issue. The UK views the promotion and protection of human rights as inalienable rights in themselves, and as a precondition to security and global economic growth.",,"Baroness Anelay of St Johns",,"2015-12-30T14:36:04.817Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439524/answer","Biography information for Baroness Anelay of St Johns","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439524/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439524/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2015-12-17","Human Rights","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what priority the FCO gives to the promotion and protection of human rights globally.","false","Biography information for The Marquess of Lothian",,"The Marquess of Lothian","HL4709"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439526","Leader of the House of Lords","false","2016-01-05","<p>The process for prayers was last considered by the Procedure Committee in December 2012 (3rd Report, Session 2012-13, HL Paper 81). Any change to the present arrangements would be a matter for the Procedure Committee, in consultation with the Lords Spiritual.</p>",,"Baroness Stowell of Beeston",,"2016-01-05T15:53:00.21Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439526/answer","Biography information for Baroness Stowell of Beeston","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439526/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439526/answer",,,,,"92",,"Leader of the House of Lords","2015-12-17","House of Lords: Prayer","2","House of Lords","To ask the Leader of the House when revising the process for prayers was last considered, and what consideration has been given to including an opportunity for additional prayers following a national or international tragedy or disaster.","false","Biography information for Lord Storey",,"Lord Storey","HL4711"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439527","Department for Transport","false","2015-12-22","<p>The government recognises that Liverpool is a major city and a significant market. Evidence from Liverpool City Region has been assessed but no decision has yet been made on the Phase Two route other than the route to Crewe.</p><br /><p>Liverpool will benefit from day one of HS2. Phase One will cut 28 minutes from the journey time between Liverpool and London. Accelerating the line to Crewe will reduce journeys by a further 14 minutes.</p><br /><p>HS2 will ensure that it maximises the synergies with the Northern Powerhouse, to make the most of the two networks. In this way opportunities may be created for Liverpool to benefit still further.</p>",,"Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon",,"2015-12-22T11:38:06.457Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439527/answer","Biography information for Lord Ahmad of Wimbledon","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439527/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439527/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2015-12-17","High Speed 2 Railway Line: Liverpool","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government what assessment they have made of the 20 Miles More group's campaign to extend HS2 to Liverpool.","false","Biography information for Lord Storey",,"Lord Storey","HL4712"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439528","Department for Culture, Media and Sport","false","2016-01-06","<p>Ofcom's Broadcasting Code sets the standards for television that broadcasters must follow and takes into account the British Board of Film Classification's guidelines and classification decisions in its guidance to broadcasters. The Code also includes rules for protecting children, such as a watershed on television to prevent unsuitable material being shown before 9pm when children could be watching.</p>",,"Baroness Neville-Rolfe",,"2016-01-06T14:44:09.227Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439528/answer","Biography information for Baroness Neville-Rolfe","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439528/answer",,,,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439528/answer",,,,,"10","Culture, Media and Sport","Culture, Media and Sport","2015-12-17","Film: Classification Schemes","2","House of Lords","To ask Her Majesty’s Government why they do not require British Board of Film Classification categories for films shown on television, unlike films in cinemas or on video and DVD.","false","Biography information for Lord Storey",,"Lord Storey","HL4713"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/439529","Department for Energy and Climate Change","false","2015-12-23","<p>The size and performance of the UK low carbon economy report published by the Department for Business, Innovation and Skills [1] estimated that in 2013 the low carbon economy generated £70.8 billion in turnover [2] for those businesses operating <em>directly </em>in the sector. This grew to £121.7 billion when the supply chain is included. The breakdown of the £121.7 billion by sector for direct and indirect activity in 2013 is published in the report and is reproduced in Table 1 below. The report has not assessed the proportion of spend by different groups (e.g. government, local government, business, individuals, and other bodies) for these sectors.</p><br /><p><strong><em>Table 1: Turnover by sector: 2013 (£million nominal)</em></strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Sector of low carbon economy</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Direct [3] Turnover </strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Indirect [4]</strong> <strong>Turnover </strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Total Turnover </strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Onshore wind</p></td><td><p>3,600</p></td><td><p>2,700</p></td><td><p>6,300</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Offshore wind</p></td><td><p>2,000</p></td><td><p>1,500</p></td><td><p>3,500</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Nuclear energy</p></td><td><p>7,700</p></td><td><p>4,400</p></td><td><p>12,100</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Hydroelectric energy</p></td><td><p>1,100</p></td><td><p>800</p></td><td><p>1,900</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Marine</p></td><td><p>200</p></td><td><p>200</p></td><td><p>400</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Solar PV</p></td><td><p>5,000</p></td><td><p>3,500</p></td><td><p>8,400</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Energy generation from waste and biomass</p></td><td><p>2,400</p></td><td><p>1,800</p></td><td><p>4,100</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Carbon capture and storage</p></td><td><p>400</p></td><td><p>200</p></td><td><p>600</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Biomass equipment</p></td><td><p>1,500</p></td><td><p>1,100</p></td><td><p>2,500</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Geothermal</p></td><td><p>500</p></td><td><p>300</p></td><td><p>800</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Heat pumps</p></td><td><p>1,900</p></td><td><p>1,300</p></td><td><p>3,100</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Solar thermal</p></td><td><p>500</p></td><td><p>300</p></td><td><p>800</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Heat networks</p></td><td><p>100</p></td><td><p>100</p></td><td><p>200</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Energy-efficient lighting</p></td><td><p>2,100</p></td><td><p>1,400</p></td><td><p>3,500</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Insulation</p></td><td><p>3,100</p></td><td><p>2,400</p></td><td><p>5,500</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Energy-efficient windows and doors</p></td><td><p>1,500</p></td><td><p>1,300</p></td><td><p>2,800</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Heat recovery and ventilation</p></td><td><p>900</p></td><td><p>600</p></td><td><p>1,500</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Energy controls and control systems</p></td><td><p>1,400</p></td><td><p>900</p></td><td><p>2,200</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Sustainable architecture and buildings</p></td><td><p>500</p></td><td><p>400</p></td><td><p>900</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Low carbon advisory services</p></td><td><p>1,700</p></td><td><p>1,100</p></td><td><p>2,800</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Low carbon finance</p></td><td><p>600</p></td><td><p>300</p></td><td><p>900</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Recycling - recovery and reprocessing of materials from waste</p></td><td><p>12,400</p></td><td><p>9,500</p></td><td><p>21,800</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Alternative fuels</p></td><td><p>15,200</p></td><td><p>10,900</p></td><td><p>26,100</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Low emission vehicles</p></td><td><p>4,600</p></td><td><p>4,200</p></td><td><p>8,800</p></td></tr><tr><td><p><strong>Total low carbon</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>70,800</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>50,900</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>121,700</strong></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p><em>Source: BIS (March 2015); the Size and Performance of the UK Low Carbon Economy</em></p><p>